text:
Everything I said is proven in the Bible, whether or not someone wants to believe it or see it.  That is my proof and what backs up my statements. Just because all of Christianity does not agree with it doesn't make it incorrect. Many people hold beliefs held on by traditions and nothing else. I know that the devil has influenced and created many different religions but nothing compares to the Bible.

&#x200B;

Not sure if you have since I don't know you but you should check out one of the posts I have made on a study in Proverbs. Pretty easy to follow along. Explains the mystery of God and what it is.

&#x200B;

God does respect choices, which is why there is sin in the world and why He allowed the devil to sin in the first place. Had He just destroyed the devil as soon as He did something wrong, the devil's accusations would have been proven correct that God is just selfish and evil, but allowing the devil to play out his own actions and the consequences to those actions shows that God is good and loving. There are guidelines in the Bible. Most Christians don't understand them because of a very popular teaching that laws were done away with at the cross when that isn't true. There is so much misunderstanding due to traditional teachings and lack of study that people simply just don't get it.

&#x200B;

Most people, I'm sure we can agree, see hell as this place the devil is in charge of and a person will be tortured for all eternity because of some wrong doing or maybe being atheist for a short time, like example 10 years. How does that make any sense? Why would a loving God punish a person for 10000000x years for only 10? Answer: He wouldn't. This is a common teaching, but it isn't any where in the Bible. Yes, there is a punishment, but it isn't forever. It has a time limit, unknown what that time is, but it does have an ending. People would be absolutely miserable knowing others are suffering when they are enjoying things.

&#x200B;

Big picture friend. God doesn't want His children to live experiencing pain and suffering and sadness, which is why He will reward them with everlasting life and happiness. God wants a relationship with us and can only give that reward with those who want the same thing. If someone hated God and had to spend forever worshipping Him when they really didn't want to would be miserable forever. God doesn't want that. It's like a person's relationship with their children. I don't want my children to suffer and have harm come to them. I would that they were happy and perfect and had everything they needed. God is the same way for us.

&#x200B;

To me, it isn't about what religion is right or wrong. It is about following God and His word. If a religion just happens to fall in line with that, wonderful. If not, there is probably a misunderstanding there. I can't speak much on other religious books, but I've read some of the book of Mormon and that one doesn't fall in line with the Bible, which is the standard I use to see how everything else "religious" measures up. There are understandings Christians have that simply don't fall in line with the Bible, and that makes for a lot of confusion and, I believe, discouragement. Turns people away from God because they don't really understand the greater picture.

Example: People use the term "God's will" incorrectly. Like a child with cancer. "If it is Your will God". Why would God want a child to have cancer? That wasn't His will at all. He allows things to happen, but that doesn't mean He wanted it or willed it to happen. That is another BIG misunderstanding.
